Czech discovery: a substance that also works in ́stamped ́ HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works in the viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the compound does not affect common virus variants as much as one of the existing medicines.
The disease AIDS cannot be cured yet.
However, the patient can prolong his or her life and prevent the proliferation of HIV viruses in the body.
However, your intake is accompanied by a number of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of viral multiplication also results in the development of sg. Resistentviruses, against which no drugs are effective anymore.
The work of the experts of three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, the VSCHT (Chemisch-technische Hochschule) Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to dealing with viral resistance.
They have shown that the substances referred to as metalocarborans affect the protein that is responsible for the proliferation of the HIV virus.
The metalocarborans are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block viral multiplication in a different way than any medicine used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists arrive at new ́improved ́ compounds, which were prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus protein.
The metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-faceted cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms, coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Perpetual and persistent virus
HIV protease is the protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus split caused by HIV protease, no mature virus particles would be created.
When we eliminate HIV protease, we also eliminate the proliferation of the virus in the patient's body, the scientists explain in the press report published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the work published in the journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically changed.
Slightly weaker, but more reliable
The impact of this series of substances against HIV protease was tested in the test tube, including their resistant (resistant) variants obtained from HIV infected patients.
The effect of metalocarborans on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as with the clinically used medicines, but it does not lose its effect on the resistant variants, against which the medicinal products used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action and its other properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical formation, make metalocarboranes interesting compounds for further research into the development of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlina Rezacova, head of the Structural Biology Laboratory of the Institutes of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
