The ice it marks melts at alarming speed and takes life with it that can't survive anywhere else.
Oil, gas, shipping and fishing interests have recently entered open water, with diplomats, lawyers and now authors in their keel water.
Richard Ellis, an author and illustrator, draws in "On Thin Ice" (original title: "On Thin Ice") a natural history of the icon of the north, the polar bear.
Experienced in the complicated history and politics of whaling, he describes the long tradition of Arctic explorers who have proved themselves hunting polar bears.
Admiral Nelson's encounter with a polar bear as a brave 14-year-old ensign to the lake, who only fought with the rifle butt of his musket, is certainly a legend, but others are true.
Young bears caught swimming behind the bodies of their recently killed mothers were taken to zoos and circuses.
A circus performance at the beginning of the 20th century showed 75 polar bears at a performance.
Even today, zoos still typically have one millionth of the life area of a wild old animal. The climate is rarely suitable: the polar bear in Singapore became all green from the algae growing in the hollow hairs of its fur.
