Ellis refers to the reports of other authors and historians and often returns to the threat posed by hunters for the survival of the species.
Although banned in Norway, America and Russia, the killing continues in Greenland and Canada, where hunters in helicopters and motor-sled-driving Inuit use powerful assault rifles to track down their prey.
Ironically, the ice will remain the longest in the waters in the north of these two hunting nations.
In his new book "After the Ice", Alun Anderson, a former editor of the science magazine "New Scientist", offers a clear and disturbing description of Arctic science and a gripping insight into how the future could develop.
Not that scientists have all the answers.
Neither atmospheric scientists nor oceanographers can adequately explain the speed of the changes.
But that is not due to a lack of explanations.
The pioneering voyages of Fridtjof Nansen at the end of the 19th and early 20th centuries gave us a glimpse of the swirling of the pack ice for the first time.
Undersea boats due in the Cold War the shifting ridges at the underrun.
A useful addition are satellite measurements and the large-scale deployment of measuring probes on icebergs, but much is still achieved by intrepid people camping outside in the cold.
Anderson takes a look at the strange, tiny world of the inflow system within the Arctic ice formed by saltwater troughs compressed during freezing.
But, from the bear on the ice to the microscopic miracles in the ice, all are threatened when the summer ice once passes, which is expected between 2013 and 2050.
