Marine infantrymen were among the 6,000 who laid wreaths in Arlington
Chief Private De'Angello Robinson travelled seven hours by bus to lay a single wreath on the grave of a soldier he had never met.
For him and the other naval infantrymen who undertook the journey from Camp Johnson in Jacksonville, North Carolina, to the National Cemetery in Arlington to decorate graves, the day was a tribute to the men and women in whose footsteps they have stepped.
In a few months, wherever we're brought back from, we could be, Robinson said about the fallen soldiers.
If we were, I'd wish someone would do the same for me, so I'm trying to show my respect.
He was one of more than 6,000 volunteers who had gathered on Saturday morning to lay wreaths on the graves of veterans in several sections of the Arlington cemetery.
Morrill Worcester, owner of Worcester Wreath Company in Harrington, Maine, established this tradition in 1992 when he and some others decided to decorate several hundred graves at the cemetery in Arlington.
It is now an 18-year-old tradition and Morrill and his wife Karen, who undertake this journey every year, stop in various cities along the way to conduct events dedicated to people in the military and victims of terrorism.
Worcesters also founded a non-profit organization, Wreaths Across Amerika (Kräze all over America), which has also extended the event to other states.
This year, volunteers placed more than 16,000 wreaths on the tombs at the Arlington Cemetery, in areas at the Pentagon, on graves at the Fayetteville National Cemetery in Arkansas, at Battery Park in New York, and at the memorial for United Airlines Flight 93 in Shanksville, Pennsylvania.
The Walmart Foundation donated more than $150,000 for the second time to purchase and transport the wreaths.
Charleen Hunt, 70, from Westminster said she made the trip to Arlington in memory of her husband, a deceased professional soldier.
Although her husband is not buried in Arlington, Hunt said this is her way of giving back to those who made sacrifices.
She said that this is a small contribution on how we civilians can support our soldiers.
It's like visiting a family grave.
Wrapped in layers of warm clothing, the volunteers wandered across the extensive lawns and hills of the cemetery.
The volunteers had older graves from the 1st and 2nd World War and the Vietnam War as a target, as these are not visited as often as the newer graves, according to the organizers.
The mood was cheerful, children played and couples held hands while they carried the fresh pine branches to the greying tombstones.
Each round wreath was dark green with a small red loop attached to the upper part.
Section 60, which is located nearby and where mainly veterans of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan are buried, remained almost calm.
The United Service Organizations donated 1,000 wreaths to decorate this section, but the grim mood of the current wars filled this area.
Individuals cried openly, others prayed, and families and friends held together in the icy air.
Some read aloud the names carved into stone, while others bowed down to small black and white maps, which had been put into the damp mud for those whose gravestones had not yet been completed.
Sandra Lockwood was one of the many mothers who shed bitter tears in front of her son's grave.
She drove 8 hours from Zanesfield, Ohio to visit the tomb of Marineinfranterie Sergeant David Shane Spicer, who fell in combat in July.
No one should ever forget why we are free..., my son paid for it, she said.
"When I've been gone for a long time, I want someone to remember him."
US government contractor arrested by Cuban authorities
The Cuban government has arrested a US government contractor who sold mobile phones and notebook computers in the country, said representatives of the State Department on Saturday.
The contractor, who has not yet been identified, is working for Development Alternatives Inc. based in Bethesda.
The company is working on projects for customers, such as USAID, the U.S. Agency for International Development and the World Bank.
Consular officials from the U.S. Interest Group in Havana are trying to gain access to the prisoner who was arrested on December 5.
The specific charges have not yet been published, although, according to Cuban law, a Cuban citizen or a foreign visitor can be arrested for almost anything under the charge of "hazard".
All so-called counterrevolutionary activities, including light protests and critical writings, are at risk of arrest.
Anti-government graffiti and statements are considered a serious crime.
Cuba has a growing blogger community led by popular reporter Yoani Sánchez, who often describes how she and her husband are persecuted and attacked by government officials.
Sánchez has repeatedly requested permission to leave the country to receive prices, but this has always been rejected.
The arrest of an American contractor is likely to increase tensions between the Castro brother's communist government in Cuba and the Obama administration, which had sought a "slow" approach to improving relations with the island.
The news of the arrest was first reported Friday night by the New York Times.
The new US policy places great value on the fact that the United States will provide a return if the Cuban government takes concrete steps in this direction, such as releasing political prisoners and creating more space for opposition.
Mobile phones and notebooks are legal in Cuba, although they are new and sought after products in a country where the average salary of a government employee is $15 a month.
The Cuban government has only allowed ordinary citizens to buy a mobile phone since this year, they are used primarily for sending text messages, as a 15-minute telephone call would cost a daily wage.
Internet use on the island is extremely restricted.
It is accessible in expensive hotels and there for foreign visitors and at some government offices, such as universities.
Cubans who wish to log in often have to report their names to the government.
Access to many websites is restricted.
In Cuba, the arrest of an American is rare.
Most of the few U.S. citizens who are in prison in Cuba are behind bars for crimes such as drug smuggling, said Gloria Berbena, the press spokesperson for the U.S. interest representation in Havana.
Berbena said she couldn't give any more information about the arrest.
The arrest and detention are clearly wrong.
An activity that would be legal in any other free society - the delivery of free mobile phones - is a crime in Cuba, said Jose Miguel Vivanco, head of the American section of the "Human Rights Watch" group, who recently issued a hard report on freedom in Cuba entitled "New Castro, same Cuba", a reference to the inauguration of Raul Castro as the country's leader, replacing the sick older brother Fidel.
Vivaco said that the defendants were very often arrested, convicted and imprisoned within one day.
He said that probably any solution would be political and that the Cuban government often provokes a negative reaction in the United States, just at the time when both countries are moving towards each other for more willingness to engage in dialogue.
Pakistani government officials uncover plan to send men to Afghanistan
Pakistani authorities discovered on Saturday a supposedly leading head of a conspiracy aimed at sending five men from Northern Virginia to Afghanistan to kill U.S. soldiers, saying that they hope this case could help uncover an extensive network of terrorist recruiters searching the Internet for radicalized young men.
Investigators said they had been looking for an opaque insurgent, known as Saifullah, who had invited the men to Pakistan after he had tracked them down because one of them had made consenting comments on terrorist attacks on the YouTube Internet video page.
Saifullah became the leader of these men after their arrival in Pakistan, trying to help them reach the remote area in Pakistan's tribal belt, which is home to Al Qaeda and its terrorist training camps.
But a representative of Pakistan's intelligence who was briefed on the matter said on Saturday that Saifullah could not convince the al-Qaeda leaders that the men are not part of a CIA conspiracy to infiltrate the terrorist network.
As a result, they were detained for days in the eastern city of Sargodha, far from the inhospitable mountains in the northwest, which have become a terrorist refuge.
They were considered part of a covert operation.
Therefore, they were rejected, said the government official, who wanted to remain anonymous due to the sensitivity of the matter.
The government official said that the men were by no means discouraged and continued to seek the right recommendations to gain access to the al-Qaeda camps when they were arrested by the Pakistani correctional authorities.
The case of the five men - who remain in Pakistan and are being questioned by the FBI - underlines the crucial role of recruiters in identifying future terrorists and possibly even more important, in deciding who is trustworthy.
Since the attacks of September 11, 2001, U.S. intelligence has made it a matter of utmost urgency to accommodate human assets within Al Qaeda.
The recruiters of the organization act as porters who do not let in those whose commitment to the Holy War is not serious enough and those who could be spies.
American wannabe recruits are subjected to a special test by A Qaeda, analysts said.
However, due to their potential access to US targets and their propaganda value, they are also considered to be tremendously attractive to the group.
Evan Kohlmann, senior analyst of the NEFA Foundation based in the United States, said that terrorist groups have also become much more cautious in recent years with regard to whom they allow access, because the U.S. intelligence services have become experts in their recruitment methods.
If you try to introduce someone into these groups, what better way could you go than to follow the recruitment model that so many have already followed?, said Kohlmann.
The model is now much more based on the Internet.
Tens of thousands of protesters call for climate action in Copenhagen
Tens of thousands of protesters marched through the streets here on Saturday and demanded bolder action on climate protection from negotiators in the Bella Congress Centre of the city.
Protesters said that 100,000 people had joined the event, while police estimates tended to run out of about 25,000.
The event went relatively peacefully, although a handful of masked activists lit small explosive devices near some government buildings in the city centre.
On a day when little happened in the UN-sponsored climate negotiations, thousands of activists with banners wandered through the city saying "There is no Planet B" and one in Spanish saying "The Earth says "Enough".
Some stars joined the protest, for example the Danish model, photographer Helena Christensen, who said that her travels to Peru, her mother's country of birth, made her aware of the heartbreaking problems the country has to deal with due to the already noticeable effects of climate change.
That is part of the reasons why I decided to take part in the big demonstration - to pass on the word and appeal to the world leaders to bring about a fair, ambitious and binding agreement, she said.
It's not an easy task, but it has to be done now and there's no way around it anymore.
The police stopped the protesters from getting too close to the Bella Centre and said they had arrested 19 people, mainly due to the fact that they were either masked or carrying pocket knives.
Under Danish law, these actions are prohibited in demonstrations.
According to a spectator who did not want to be named because he was involved in the climate negotiations, masked protesters in black clothes lit several explosive devices near the main channel in Copenhagen, near which several ministries are located.
They threw them near the buildings, he said, adding that they began as flares, but then followed by "a few big explosions."
Inside the convention center, people gathered in front of television screens to follow the demonstration all afternoon.
But the protest apparently did not reach the awareness of the main officials, such as Su Wie, China's chief climate negotiator.
When asked if he thought that the demonstration had a constructive effect on international considerations, he replied in English: "This is something I was not aware of."
He then continued in Mandarin and said, "Because the venue is large, I can't hear what's happening outside."
He noted that it depends on the individual's perspective whether the demonstration would harm or help.
It shows the concentration of the general public and various sectors on the topic of climate change, he said.
On the other hand, "you can also say that they disturb the negotiations or the freedom of other people".
Test data show persistent breed gap
The evidence of mathematics performance was welcomed last week to the public schools in Washington D.C.
Although Washington District is still far behind the country's schools producing top performances, the evidence shows that the fourth and eighth graders have made faster progress over the past two years than cities including Atlanta, Chicago and New York.
But what is included in the latest National Assessment of Educational Progress (NAEP) figures is the persistent performance gap between African American and white students, both at local and national levels.
The average score of the white fourth graders from Washington D.C. rose from 262 to 270 (on a scale of 500) in the last two years, but that of their African-American peers rose only by three points from 209 to 212.
The performance gap actually rose from 53 to 58 points between 2007 and 2009.
The progress of the African-American eighth graders remained basically the same, falling by a statistically negligible point from 245 to 244.
The average score of white pupils was not included in the test data as the sample size was not large enough.
The picture over a six-year period is also not more encouraging.
The gap separating white and black fourth graders in 2003 when the first NAEP in this district was captured was 60 scales points (262 to 202).
And although the score that children of both groups have achieved has grown over this period of time, the difference has hardly decreased with now 58 points.
Some of the district's educational supporters expressed concern last week that the results celebrated by school chancellor Michelle A. Rhee and Democratic mayor Adrian M. Fenty were largely driven by white students who are already powerful children anyway.
This suggests that we raised the overall score by treating those at the top of the scale, which is problematic and difficult, said Jeff Smith, board member of D.C. Voice, a non-profit group that advocates educational equality in Washington D.C.
I do not jump up and down for a span of two or three points, said Democratic Washington City Councillor Kwame R. Brown, who has a daughter in the fourth grade of Eaton primary school.
Brown, a frequent critic of Rhee's management style, said the message of the exam score is that the city's middle schools urgently need attention.
Of course, you always want to see the positive signs, I respect that.
But what scares me is that we don't spend nearly the time and energy we need to use for our middle school.
Rhee said the district must continue to find better ways to meet the needs of low-performance students.
This autumn, for example, some teachers are being trained to use a new reading curriculum, the Wilson Reading System, aimed at students in the upper classes of primary and middle school, who have not mastered basic literacy skills at the beginning of their school career and who are significantly behind their peers of the same age.
Everyday mathematics, a curriculum that brings games and lifelike experiences to the fore from kindergarten to sixth grade, was brought to Washington under former senior school inspector Clifford Janey and this curriculum is attributed to some of the NAEP progress reported last week.
I believe that we must continue to work to make the best measures available to students below grades, Rhee said.
Others say that the NAEP results highlight the question of whether Rhee can continue to improve the overall performance of the system while continuing to provide the additional money and resources for the low-performance schools that are needed to reduce the gap.
This is a serious dilemma for Michelle Rhee, said Bruce Fuller, Professor of Education at the University of California in Berkeley, who is investigating urban exam results.
The conventional remedy is to focus its resources and management reforms on the schools located in the poorest areas of Washington D.C.
The objective could have political repercussions that work against this important item on the agenda.
The weak point is, of course, as with other city school inspectors, that they are trying to keep the white and black middle class.
Our focus is to ensure that we build a system of great schools.
We need to strengthen our schools in the neighbourhoods so that all families, regardless of where they live, can be sure that their children can receive excellent public education.
Janey, who is now a school inspector in Newark, said this week in an interview that one of the most important elements for closing the performance gap is to extend the traditional public school year, which is currently 180 days in Washington, to compete with the charter schools.
One must increase the school year to approximately 200 days in order to have the power to change, said Janey, who came to an agreement with his teachers' union last year on 185 days a year, which he regarded as "a milestone" on the way to a greater increase in the next contract.
Higher education for more people than the future
The coach reaches the Gettysburg College with a loud whistle.
Graciela Rodriguez, 12, gets out and blinks a moment at the sight of the white columns, the brick facades and the emerald green lawn.
Graciela's parents barely finished high school in El Salvador.
Until recently, Graciela, who was recovered in Silver Spring and now lives in Riverdale, had never set foot on a college campus.
Their attitude and that of the other eighth graders of the group, who explore Gettysburg, where teaching costs 38,690 dollars per year, was more that of an awe-inspiring visitor than that of an enthusiastic future student.
"Yes! I will be here soon!" cried Graciela, who would like to study medicine when the leader announced that they had now entered the building for science.
"Wow, really?" she said thoughtfully when she was told the low professor-to-student ratio of the school.
The college in Pennsylvania was the 7th one the children visited on their three-day tour and now they have fully absorbed the intended message: The question is not whether to go to college.
The question is where.
On the one hand, there is growing concern about the large number of children born in the United States of Hispanic immigrants who do not finish high school or become pregnant as teenagers, but on the other hand there are hundreds of thousands who receive the college education needed to get into the middle class.
In truth, one in five of these "second generation" of Hispanic Americans completes college – which is a remarkable achievement as many of their immigrant parents, mostly from Mexico or Central America, came to the United States without having graduated high school.
Their success stories are important, researchers say, because they show the way forward for a generation that will play a huge role in the country's workforce.
Those who study powerful children say they often have a natural affinity for school and an inherent drive for success.
Many of them also have parents who set their children high goals and find ways to compensate for their lack of familiarity with American schools.
But counseling programs also play a major role by helping Graciela and millions of children like her to get to college, especially if these efforts persist over a long period of time.
If you look at low-income children whose parents do not have the experience and skills to help them find their way through the system, then a single measure will not solve the problem at any time, said Patricia Gándara, researcher at the University of California in Davis, who studied Hispanic American students.
We need to think about providing these children with a supportive network from preschool to high school.
The federal program that Graciela's college tour had funded is a useful example.
It is known as GEAR UP - Turning up a gear - and provides more than $300 million a year for local school systems to launch college prep programs that start when low-income students are in middle school and continue running until they have graduated high school.
According to the US Department of Education, since 1999, the program has helped more than 10 million students, more than 60% of whom have gone to college.
Iraqi Ministry of Oil signs contracts with 10 foreign oil companies
Despite concerns about violence and political instability, at two auctions completed on Saturday, the Iraqi government has been able to persuade larger oil companies to rebuild their damaged infrastructure.
The ten contracts concluded with foreign oil companies by the Iraqi Ministry of Oil suggest that China, Russia and European oil companies are ready to play an important role in the renovation of the Iraqi oil industry, which has been paralyzed for decades by war and economic sanctions.
American companies could only book shares in two of the 10 auctioned fields for themselves.
Seven American companies had paid for participation in the second auction, which began on Friday.
The only company that has made a bid has made the shorter one.
Two American companies were able to conclude contracts for fields auctioned in June.
The thinly sown representatives of American oil multinationals in opening up the Iraqi oil industry surprised the analysts.
Iraq has finally opened its doors after 6 years of war and instead of US companies, Asians and Europeans are giving way, said Ruba Husari, the editor of Iraq Oil Forum, an online news service.
There will be no further offers in Iraq for a long time.
Security concerns, which were further underlined by massive coordinated bombings on Tuesday and political instability caused by the withdrawal of the US military, have probably deterred American oil companies from doing so, analysts said they would be more committed to Iraq, which has the world's third largest proven crude oil reserves.
US companies have been disadvantaged in some cases because competitors, especially the Chinese and other state-controlled energy companies, have significantly lower wage costs and are more likely to take risks because they do not have to account for shareholders.
Exxon-Mobil and Occidental Petroleum Inc. were the only American companies that could enter into contracts with the ministry.
Larger US companies, such as Chevron and ConocoPhillips, which maintain close relations with the Iraqi Ministry of Oil and have been assisted by technical advice in recent years, have run out.
The Russian companies Lukoil and Gazprom were the main players in two of the contracts awarded this weekend.
The state-owned China National Petroleum Corporation has offered for more contracts than any other company and was able to go home with large packages of contracts for two larger fields.
We all know, oil ministry spokesman Assam Jihad said, that China is on its way to becoming one of the greats of the world economy as well as a technology power.
We are convinced that the Chinese company can compete with its competitors and will fulfil its obligations to Iraq.
Companies pre-selected for bid submission gave bids, which were then compared to the fee per barrel of oil the ministry was willing to pay to increase the output of each field beyond the current level.
Top planner of Al Qaeda apparently killed in Pakistan
In an obvious U.S. missile attack along the Pakistani border with Afghanistan, a top al-Qaeda planner is reported to have been killed this week, according to representatives of the U.S. counterterrorism campaign on Friday.
This would be, if it were to be confirmed, the second deadly attack on a high leader of the terrorist organization this autumn.
Saleh al-Somali was one of the two Arabs who according to US sources and Pakistani officials of the region were said to have been killed by a number of rockets that hit their vehicle on Tuesday near the city of Miran Shah in the province of North Waziristan.
Local authorities reported that the missiles were fired by a drone type deployed by the CIA in Pakistan's lawless tribal belt.
They drove in a white vehicle towards the Afghan border when the car was hit, a government representative of a Pakistani civilian intelligence agency from Miran Shah said by phone.
Locals suspected of belonging to the militants ran to the site and quickly took everything that was left of the "completely destroyed bodies".
The local authorities could not confirm the identity of the victims, but two U.S. counter-terrorism representatives cited undetermined evidence that Somali was among the dead.
Somali was described as the leading military planner of Al Qaeda, who led operations of terrorist groups outside the Afghanistan-Pakistan region.
He was involved in conspiracies around the world, noted a senior official who wanted to remain anonymous, and pointed to the delicate character of U.S. airstrikes on Pakistani soil.
If one assumes its central role as given, this also included the planning of attacks against the US and Europe.
He took strategic instructions from the top leaders of Al Qaeda and implemented them in operational planning for possible terrorist attacks.
The second American official said Somali has quickly ascended into the al-Qaeda hierarchy and maintained best ties to other extremist groups in the region.
He may not be known to some Americans, the second official said, but this does not diminish the danger he posed to us and our allies.
If his death were confirmed, Somali would be the second leading Al-Qaeda or Taliban leader killed since September when in a similar attack Najmuddin Jalolov, the leader of a militant faction in the tribal area and three other top activists were killed.
The rate of attacks by CIA drones has decreased from an average of six operations per month to two, according to a summary by the Long War Journal, a website run by a non-profit organization.
The decline can be based on improved tactics of terrorist groups that have taken steps to reduce their vulnerability while brutally killing suspected informants, the side reported.
UN leader in Kabul will resign
The UN's leading envoy to Afghanistan, Kai Eide, said on Friday that he would resign from office in March, ending a stormy term clouded by allegations of widespread corruption in the UN-backed Afghan presidential election.
Eide's departure occurs when the Obama administration has decided to send another 30,000 U.S. soldiers to Afghanistan.
The UN envoy said he supported the troop increase, but he also expressed his concerns that the US timetable for military withdrawal, which is scheduled to begin in 18 months, could cause other NATO governments to withdraw their armed forces.
We need to accelerate the construction of Afghan security forces and thereby send the right signal to the Afghans that they can trust the international community, said Eide in a telephone interview from Kabul.
The commitment must be long-term.
The Norwegian diplomat also urged the United States and other military powers to increase the number of international civilian helpers to help with Afghanistan's political transition.
The increase in troops on the military side must correspond to an increase on the civilian side, he said.
Eide said that he did not resign from office, but only fulfilled an agreement made to his family in March 2008 to remain in Kabul for only two years.
He said he wanted the notification to the UN.
Secretary General Ban Ki-moon now forward so that he has time to provide for a replacement.
What I said is that he better start looking for a successor, said Eide.
When I came here, there was a two-month vacuum between my predecessor's departure and my arrival.
Ban has started to search for a replacement, according to UN representatives.
The UN representatives say that he has considered the Swedish-Italian-born Staffan di Mistura, who recently led the UN mission in Baghdad and the Frenchman Jean-Marie Guéhenno, who previously led UN peacekeeping operations.
Eide's position in Afghanistan was put to the test after his former deputy, Peter W. Galbraith, accused him in September of favoring President Hamid Karzai in the country's presidential election and covering up evidence of massive election fraud.
Oaths have rejected all accusations, but he also said that the allegations of Galbraith - who was fired - "have undoubtedly harmed the mission because there was already a great deal of scepticism regarding international interference in the election".
Eide said he recommended the appointment of a leading civilian representative to coordinate the relief efforts of the American-led forces in Afghanistan.
He also urged that the UN leadership allow his successor to hire more staff from the United States and other Western countries who donate to the Afghan mission, saying that this would strengthen their confidence in the proper use of their money.
Eide expressed his disappointment at restricting his forces in Afghanistan and said that the cumbersome UN recruitment arrangements have undermined his ability to bring in capable people.
The UN rules are designed in such a way that since May, he said, I have only been able to hire one person.
This is catastrophic and must not go on like this.
US Secretary of Defense Gates: Iran faces additional sanctions
Defense Minister Robert M. Gates said Friday that the world powers will soon impose "significant additional sanctions" on Iran because he did not participate in talks about his nuclear plans.
Gates spoke to a group of approximately 300 U.S. soldiers in northern Iraq during a 7-day journey through the war zones in Afghanistan and Iraq and played down the prospect of a military action against the Islamic Republic of Iran.
In Iran, there are no good choices, he said in response to a soldier's question about the likelihood of such a development.
"One of the things that lie on my soul is, if we have learned anything from Iraq over the past six years, that is war's own unpredictability."
The Obama administration is considering a sanction package aimed at Iran's military and political elite, but Gates has announced that some sanctions may also affect the average Iranian.
He said that a "package of positive and negative incentives" is required "to convince the Iranian government that it is actually less protected with nuclear weapons" because "their people will suffer tremendously" from the sanctions.
On Friday, in a statement by the White House spokesman, Robert Gibbs, the American government joined the European leaders in warning that Iran must face "credible" consequences if it fails to comply with the demands of the UN Security Council and its nuclear monitoring organisation, the International Atomic Energy Agency.
Iran continues to claim that knowledge of nuclear technology is to be gained only for peaceful purposes.
During talks in Geneva on 1 October, Iran said that it would resume talks to limit its nuclear program and would dispense with a substantial portion of its stock of enriched uranium in exchange for much needed nuclear fuel for its medical research reactor.
The US government has pushed for this kind of agreement to build trust between the two parties and gain time for negotiations.
But Iran seems to have left negotiations on the preliminary agreements since that time -- in part, experts say, because the Iranian leadership disagrees on whether they should commit themselves to the United States.
Gates said that Iran has simply left the international community behind in terms of some of the proposals they had already agreed to in early October, frankly bringing together the international community, including the Russians and Chinese, in a way that they never were in connection with important additional sanctions for Iran.
President Obama has set 31 Dec as the deadline for Iran to respond to these proposals before continuing to pursue other options, including those that Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton once called "pressive sanctions."
In a statement issued in New York, Iranian representation at the United Nations has condemned what it on Thursday called "fundamental and unfundamental claims" by some Security Council members on Iran's nuclear activities, saying that they are willing to continue talks with the United States and five other world powers "to achieve a suitable long-term solution".
Gates, who was scheduled to return to Washington last Friday, met with Iraqi Prime Minister Nuri al-Maliki in the morning before he flew to the oil-rich Kurdish region in Iraq for meetings with the soldiers in Kirkuk and with Kurdish officials in Irbil.
The tensions between the Kurds and the Arab majority in Iraq remain high, especially in terms of borders, property rights and the distribution of public revenue.
Gates urged both sides to reduce the conflict potential in order to prevent delays in US plans to reduce American troop strength from 115,000 to 50,000 by the end of August.
Gates also tried to dispel Kurdish concern about the impending withdrawal of troops. US representatives quoted Gates, who told Masud Barzani, president of the Kurdish regional government, "We will receive your security, your prosperity and your autonomy within a united Iraq.
We will not leave you."
A Change of Course in Ageing China
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters giving them lectures that "Mother Earth is too tired to entertain more children" and "One more baby means one more grave".
They learned these lessons so well that, as government officials in Shanghai, who suddenly began to change the course and encourage young couples to have more than one child, due to the low birth rate and the ageing population this summer, their answer was immediate and final: "No way."
We have already invested all our time and energy in a child.
There is nothing left for a second child, said Wang, 31, a staff manager with an 8-month-old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one-child policy in China, which has produced two generations of notoriously thick, spoiled single children, who are affectionately called "little emperors", a population crisis in the country draws up.
The average birth rate has fallen to 1.8 children per couple compared to 6 at the time this policy came into force, the UN
Department of Population Issues, while the number of population groups of 60 years and older in 2020 is expected to increase from 16.7 percent of the population by 2050 to 31.1 percent explosively. This is well above the global average of about 20 percent.
The imbalance is stronger in rich coastal cities with educated populations, such as Shanghai.
Last year, 60-year-olds and older people accounted for almost 22 percent of reported residents of Shanghai, while the birth rate was below one child per couple.
