In fact, IE (Intelligence Economique = Economic Intelligence) calls for "a proactive approach and a forward-looking perspective from all parties involved" and calls on the employees to make a commitment that is completely contrary to the instructions of authoritarian management.
That is why we are calling for an operational revolution, which would consist of placing the employees at the centre of the company's concerns on an equal footing with the customers.
The very conditional benefits of internal opinion polls
Will the internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its wage earners, stimulate this revolution in terms of management practice?
I'm afraid not.
- First of all, because I've been able to see that, given a new situation, the whole structure, after a lot of detours, finally gets to do what it's always done.
Also because authoritarianism - one of the pathologies of power - is increasing in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
And finally, because most leaders have a very simplified idea of human behavior.
Her interpretation of psychology is mechanistic from the major engineering schools.
Through intellectual comfort, they adopt the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the US "Neurosciences" and unknowingly widely disseminated by research institutes and the media.
Thus, and by suggesting that it is possible to use the "sic" to engage employees, a recent Le Figaro.fr survey by Ipsos reinforces the leaders in an attitude towards a mechanistic control system that is unsuitable for today's world.
Identifying and measuring the mobilisation factors
Instead, an operational revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies presupposes the adoption of a definitive view of human behaviour.
