Dream worlds
Some see pictures in awake state and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
The boundaries between imagination and reality are blurring not only among the mentally ill and in the drug rush.
As long as it happens in sleep, everything's fine.
When we lie in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we are allowed to indulge ourselves uninhibitedly in the wildest ideas and imaginations.
However, those who experience dreamlike conditions in waxiness, see and hear things that others do not see or hear, are usually considered crazy or drug addicts in the modern Western world, at least as a weirdo.
However, such images and voices do not arise only in the mentally ill or in the drug rush.
It is our imagination that is to blame: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels sometimes make the boundaries between dream, delusion and reality blur.
Dream-like altered waking consciousness states can occur in various forms, in the best case we call them visions, in the worst case delusion.
Even if triggers and effects may differ, the visions of mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, shamanic states of rapture, psychosis and hallucinations can be traced back to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of neuronal messenger substances of the brain - especially dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin and acetylcholine - is derailed and the interaction of different brain parts is disturbed.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts occur very frequently during schizophrenic psychosis.
Gravity has no more power over it
The connection between delusion and dream has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle saw hallucinations as a form of the dream in the awake state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, stated in 1861 a "great similarity of madness with dream states", for Sigmund Freud, the dream was even "a psychosis, with all the inconsistencies, delusions, illusions of such."
It's autumn 2001 when Henning T. turns into a comic character.
His body is two-dimensional and squeaky.
Gravity no longer has power over him, it floats on the ceiling.
He's feeling a kick.
Behind him winged devil figures with blood-red, distorted faces, fang-flessing.
They chase him, kick him with heavy, flaming boots, throw him against the walls, he feels the pain all over his body.
Loud, vicious voices roar from walls and radio.
He can't bear them anymore, the voices that insult and insult him.
Henning T. rips two cables out of the stereo, knots them to a loop and fastens them to a hook on the ceiling.
He gets on a speaker and lays the noose around his neck.
Jump.
The noose is loosened.
That's supposed to be a lesson for you, the voices in drum-peeling choir yell, "Go to the clinic and let yourself be healed!"
Today Henning T. is 40 years old, he has experienced six acute psychoses, the last is 2 years old, the first almost 20 years old.
It was triggered by LSD.
His diagnosis is schizoaffective-paranoid psychosis, he is also manic-depressive, he takes medications against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He's learned to live with his illness, he's been married for three years.
In psychosis, I have experienced the worst fear and deepest despair, he says.
The deceitful images are cruel reality
About one percent of the population suffer from schizophrenia at least once in their lives, and in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, those affected can usually no longer distinguish between the inside and the outside world, they get into an overexcited state that can lead to hallucinations, megalomania, relationship or persecution.
Especially common is voice-hearing - voices that command, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also not uncommon.
The affected person can no longer separate important things from unimportant things, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like the dream, psychosis also opens the locks to a flood of ideas and fantasies that stem from deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, senior physician of the Department of General Psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the centre of the event, everything has a meaning directed towards it.
At the same time, he gets into a passive role, he is overwhelmed by the events, much like in a dream, and he cannot actively shape them.
Schizophrenic patients therefore often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
They are not usually able to compare reality, the illusions are cruel reality, waking up is excluded.
To have experienced a hallucination once in life
Unlike in the dream, Fuchs says, "but the sensual and spatial structure of reality, which is perceived in psychosis, remains fundamentally preserved."
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of experience takes place within a real framework.
Why exactly our brain beats caprioles still puzzles researchers.
With every human being, exceptional states can cause him to lose his realism for a short time, says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that the genes are not the sole determining factors.
Researchers assume that there are minimal brain damage in those affected.
We suspect that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disrupted at an early stage of development, for example by a mother's viral disease during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But it remains a mystery how the disorder of the neuronal system comes about, which is not manifesting for many years at first.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can trigger psychosis if the disposition is present.
Hallucinogenic drugs can also trigger psychosis as they interfere with the transmitter system.
When our brains run hot
The crazy thing is, psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and swallow expensive drugs to get rid of them, others spend money on drugs to get them, says Lübeck psychology professor Erich Kasten.
Whether false images are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often only a matter of point of view.
For ten years, Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and delusions, and last year he evaluated his findings in the book "The Irreal World in Our Head".
Hallucinations are one of the typical side effects of psychosis, but also of a surprising number of other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, these often include diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer's disease and skull brain trauma.
Surprisingly, even the brain of healthy people is hallucinating under certain conditions.
Hallucinations, according to Boxes, are composed of memory contents that are usually held back.
They arise when brain areas in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or insufficiently inhibited; when our brain is running hot or even when stimulation is lacking.
Drugs can trigger this condition as well as brain damage or psychosis.
But also exasperation, stress, heartbreak or other mental states of exception.
In recent studies, up to a third of respondents claimed to have experienced hallucinations at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania and attends the Gymnasium there.
A normal girl, actually.
If it wasn't for the pictures and voices.
During the break, it may happen that a limp boy with long, dark hair responds to it.
When it answers him, the classmates look at it in surprise - no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think the shy girl is a spunky daydreamer, but Sarah K. doesn't dream, she knows.
She is awake, she hears and sees this boy, just as she hears and sees the girl in the bank next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for moments.
A pleasant feeling is that she likes the boy.
Am I crazy?, she sometimes wonders.
But she knows that this boy and the other illusions are not real and disappear again.
At night, the appearances are usually scary
Often the illusions are also a burden.
When she sits in the classroom, she can sometimes not follow the teaching material, because the teacher in her eyes and ears introduces a new classmate, while he explains mathematical equations for all the others hearing and visibly on the board.
At night, the appearances are usually scary.
When she waits for sleep in her dark room, which is far too rare and much too late, she often cannot distinguish whether she is awake or already dreaming, whether the pictures she sees are the faces or the girl with the bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, she screams at the figures.
Parents and friends wouldn't tell her about it, they'd think she was crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She passed her Abitur last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she made contact with the psychologist box on the Internet, she knows she's not crazy.
Delusion is also a work of art out of despair
If a person is socially isolated or suffers from excitement, he is most likely to have hallucinations after a while, says Kasten.
I suppose the brain is then underworked and provides its own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at 13 that the man she calls Papa since she can think is not her biological father.
Since the same brain areas are active in visual and acoustic hallucinations, which also process real impressions and sounds, it is difficult for those affected such as Sarah K. to distinguish between false images and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "takes place in the brain, the reality is there.
Hallucinations are also images that create the brain, which is why they work so real."
Even nightly dream pictures value caste as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their delusions as unreal.
Therefore, Kasten advises his patients to value hallucinations as a special ability.
Border State between Dream and Hallucination
Unfortunately, in our overly consciousness-centered world, imaginary experiences are mostly pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Department of Psychiatry and Psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
Psychosis is a serious, painful disease, but it also carries positive, creative delusion - delusion is also a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has explored the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of dream-like altered consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams, which the experiencer thinks are real and which he cannot distinguish from the waking state in retrospect.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in trauma or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis with full consciousness.
When a person is threatened with self- and world loss, for example, with persistent, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own imaginary world, which is decoupled from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of borderline between dream and hallucination.
Since coping with a situation in reality is not possible, a world change takes place, but the real situation is visualized in imagination.
An intense form of sense and meaning in a situation that is unbearable in itself, which allows us humans to create our own ability not to sink into a nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Herzwechsel" as a rescue action of the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness travels for days after a heart valve operation followed by a heart transplant, while his body is condemned to motionlessness in the intensive care unit.
Claussen dives into a self-created world, visits strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden, old man, aboard a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among nobles who produce drugs from blood.
Is transported by a Greek on a motorcycle to his home country, surfs with his hospital bed in the snow of the Alps and meets a Korean mafia.
He fully rises in the imagined event, everything is real, even later in memory.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dream is a different state, he describes his experience.
In contrast, the memories from mental travels are still clear to me after years and in minor details.
Clearer and more intense even than what was really experienced.
The intensity of this experience bursts the horizon of our other life-worldly experiences, says the psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
In the end, oneiroids, psychoses, hallucinations, and drug rush show how fragile our inner images of external reality are also in the wake.
Any change in the state of consciousness, sums up the psychologist caste, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be enriching.
