Support for braking manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As in the case of the ABS anti-lock braking system at the time and as it is now happening with the ESP stability control system, the emergency braking systems must become compulsory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly registered passenger cars and light vans, and for the remaining vehicles a waiting period has been fixed until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measure adopted by the European Union is to improve the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help prevent many rear-end accidents due to their operation.
The task of the emergency braking assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical braking manoeuvre, which the system detects on the brake pedal based on the braking strength carried out by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident were no longer able to step on the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not slowed down with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force in the braking system, thereby reducing the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car travels during the braking process.
According to a study by the EU, up to 1,100 fatal accidents in which pedestrians are harmed could be prevented every year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assistants.
There would be even fewer accidents - one in four accidents is expected to be prevented with personal injury - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
The vehicle is then equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system will help him increase the pressure on the brake pedal if it becomes necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is inevitable, the brake assistant exerts the maximum pressure on the brakes in order to keep the damage as low as possible.
